# CLOUD FUNCTIONS PATTERNS

## OpenRouter API Integration

### Model Configuration
- **ALWAYS** use a centralized model constant:
  ```javascript
  const OPENROUTER_MODEL = "google/gemini-2.0-flash-001";
  ```
- **NEVER** use `:free` suffix with paid API keys (causes routing issues, 429 errors with zero activity in logs)
- Use standard model names for reliable routing

### Required Headers
OpenRouter requires these headers for proper routing and analytics:
```javascript
headers: {
    "Authorization": `Bearer ${apiKey}`,
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "HTTP-Referer": "https://your-site.vercel.app",
    "X-Title": "Your App Name"
}
```

### Error Handling
- If API key is missing, mark for manual review instead of leaving pending
- On API errors, mark as `needs_review` with error message in `flaggedReason`
- Log errors with context: `console.error("[Layer 3] Error:", error.message)`

## Image Moderation

### Rejected Image Cleanup
When a post is approved, check for and delete any rejected images:
```javascript
if (data.imageUrl) {
    await deleteRejectedImageForPost(postRef, data.imageUrl);
}
```

### Parse Firebase Storage URLs
```javascript
if (imageUrl.includes('firebasestorage.googleapis.com')) {
    const match = imageUrl.match(/\/o\/(.+?)\?/);
    if (match) {
        filePath = decodeURIComponent(match[1]);
    }
}
```

## Testing Cloud Functions

### Mock `fetch` for API Tests
```javascript
beforeEach(() => {
    capturedFetchArgs = [];
    mockFetch = jest.fn((url, options) => {
        capturedFetchArgs.push({ url, options });
        return Promise.resolve({
            ok: true,
            json: () => Promise.resolve({
                choices: [{ message: { content: 'SAFE' } }]
            })
        });
    });
    global.fetch = mockFetch;
});
```

### Validate Request Structure
```javascript
it('should include required headers', async () => {
    await callApi('Test');
    const headers = capturedFetchArgs[0].options.headers;
    expect(headers['Authorization']).toMatch(/^Bearer /);
    expect(headers['HTTP-Referer']).toBeDefined();
    expect(headers['X-Title']).toBeDefined();
});
```

### Test Error Scenarios
```javascript
it('should handle API errors', async () => {
    mockFetch.mockResolvedValueOnce({
        ok: false,
        status: 429,
        text: () => Promise.resolve('Rate limit exceeded')
    });
    await expect(callApi('Test')).rejects.toThrow('429');
});
```

## Testing Configuration Values (Regression Guards)
**Pattern**: Test the actual configuration values sent to third-party APIs, not just response handling.

This catches misconfigurations before deployment (e.g., using `:free` model suffix with paid API keys).

### Export Config Constants for Testing
```javascript
// In index.js - export configuration for testability
const OPENROUTER_MODEL = "google/gemini-2.0-flash-001";
module.exports.OPENROUTER_MODEL = OPENROUTER_MODEL;
```

### Write Regression Tests for Config Values
```javascript
describe('OpenRouter Configuration Values', () => {
    it('uses the paid model tier and excludes free variant', () => {
        // Import the ACTUAL constant, not a mock
        const { OPENROUTER_MODEL } = require('./index');
        
        expect(OPENROUTER_MODEL).toBeDefined();
        expect(OPENROUTER_MODEL).not.toMatch(/:free$/);
        expect(OPENROUTER_MODEL).not.toContain(':free');
    });
});
```

### Why This Matters
- Tests using **inline mock functions** that hardcode values don't catch config regressions
- The `:free` suffix causes 429 errors even with paid API keys (routes through free-tier infrastructure)
- Config value tests run fast and catch issues before deployment

## Common Pitfalls
- Don't forget to restore `global.fetch` in `afterEach`
- Always mock `firebase-admin` and `firebase-functions` before requiring the module
- Use `jest.resetModules()` when testing module-level code with different mocks
- **Don't use inline mock functions** for testing API integrations - test the actual exported values

## Variable Scoping for Firestore (TDZ Prevention)

**CRITICAL**: In Cloud Function handlers, declare `const db = admin.firestore();` **ONCE at the very top** of the async function.

### The Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ) Bug
JavaScript `const` variables are hoisted but NOT initialized until their declaration line. If you have multiple `const db = ...` declarations scattered in a function, code between them can fail:

```javascript
// ❌ WRONG - Multiple declarations cause TDZ errors
exports.myFunction = onDocumentWritten({...}, async (event) => {
    // ... some code ...
    
    if (condition1) {
        const db = admin.firestore();  // First declaration
        await db.collection('logs').add({...});
    }
    
    // This code runs BEFORE the const below, but 'db' is hoisted
    // causing: ReferenceError: Cannot access 'db' before initialization
    if (condition2) {
        const threadRef = db.doc('threads/123');  // TDZ ERROR!
    }
    
    const db = admin.firestore();  // Second declaration - hoists to function scope
    await db.collection('logs').add({...});
});
```

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT - Single declaration at the top
exports.myFunction = onDocumentWritten({...}, async (event) => {
    const change = event.data;
    if (!change) return;
    
    // Initialize ONCE at the top - available throughout the function
    const db = admin.firestore();
    
    if (condition1) {
        await db.collection('logs').add({...});
    }
    
    if (condition2) {
        const threadRef = db.doc('threads/123');  // Works!
    }
    
    await db.collection('logs').add({...});  // Works!
});
```

### Debugging TDZ Errors
- Error message: `ReferenceError: Cannot access 'X' before initialization`
- Check Google Cloud Logs / Error Reporting for stack traces
- Look for multiple `const X = ...` declarations of the same variable in the function
- Chrome console errors may be **symptoms** of Cloud Function crashes, not the root cause

## Parent Document Status Propagation
When approving child documents (e.g., Posts), always update the parent document (e.g., Thread) status:
```javascript
// When approving a post, also approve the parent thread
if (action === 'approved' && item.threadId) {
    const db = admin.firestore();
    const threadRef = db.doc(`path/to/threads/${item.threadId}`);
    await threadRef.update({ status: 'approved' });
}
```

**Pattern**: Child approval → Parent visibility. Posts belong to Threads; if a post is approved but the thread is still `pending`, users won't see the thread.
